'''All that glitters is not gold''': a well-known phrase from [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]''.  

The saying in various forms goes back as far as the 12th century.[http://www.phrases.org.uk/meanings/28450.html].  It may even go back to [[Aesop]].[http://everything2.com/index.pl?node=All%20that%20glitters%20is%20not%20gold]

Shakespeare's play seems to have been the first use of the exact words.  It comes from the secondary plot, the puzzle of [[Portia]]'s boxes:

:All that glitters is not gold;
:Often have you heard that told:
:Many a man his life hath sold
:But my outside to behold:
:Gilded tombs do worms enfold.

Some sources have Shakespeare saying ''glisters'' rather than ''glitters''.

==Cultural references==
In Tolkien’s [[Lord of the rings]], one of [[Bilbo]]'s poems begins ''[[All that is Gold Does Not Glitter]]''.

[[Led Zeppelin]]'s famous song ''[[Stairway to Heaven]]'' begins 
: There's a lady who's sure all that glitters is gold
: And she's buying a stairway to heaven

